    "title": "Leading Edge and Connector Work Program",
    "plainText": "LEADING EDGE AND CONNECTOR WORK PROGRAM\n\nStep-by-step field program for leading edge work, connector exposure, tie-off decisions, and access control during steel erection\n\nPrimary basis: 29 CFR 1926.760(b)-(c), 1926.761(c), 1926.754(e), and related Subpart R requirements.\n\n1. Program Purpose and Applicability\n\nThis program applies when employees are exposed to unprotected sides or edges during active steel erection, including connector work, leading edge work during decking, and transitions between access equipment and structural steel.\n\nThis program is triggered before any connector or deck-leading-edge work begins and remains active until the area is decked, protected, or otherwise released as a normal work zone.\n\n2. Roles and Responsibilities\n\n1. The steel erection foreman shall verify that the work area, sequence, and means of access match the erection drawings and the pre-task plan before employees move to the edge or receive steel.\n\n2. The competent person shall inspect the work area, tie-off method, access route, opening condition, and drop zone controls at the start of the shift and whenever conditions change.\n\n3. Connectors and deck-leading-edge workers shall follow the approved method for movement, body position, tie-off, and access restriction and shall stop work if the area no longer matches the plan.\n\n4. The controlling contractor shall coordinate adjacent-trade access so employees not engaged in the leading edge activity do not enter the exposure zone.\n\n3. Required Pre-Task Steps and Field Procedure\n\n1. Before work starts, confirm the current steel is stable for the phase of work. The receiving member, support steel, deck support line, and any temporary bracing that protects the area shall already be in place and accepted for that stage.\n\n2. Review the exact leading edge sequence. The crew shall identify where the first worker will step, where the next sheet or member will be landed, how the edge will progress, and what point marks the end of the active leading edge for that shift.\n\n3. Confirm the fall protection method being used for that area. If the task uses personal fall arrest or restraint, the anchor point, connection method, equipment inspection status, and swing-fall exposure shall be checked before movement begins.\n\n4. If the project uses a controlled decking zone or other restricted-access method allowed by the steel erection rules, the restricted boundary shall be established before the first deck sheet is spread, and access shall be limited to employees actually engaged in the leading edge work.\n\n5. Employees shall use stable access to reach the work position. Climbing over loose members, crossing unsecured deck, or stepping through incomplete routes is not permitted as a normal means of access.\n\n6. During receiving and placement, connectors shall keep hands, feet, and body position out of the line of movement and shall not assume a member is stable until the required initial connection condition is actually complete.\n\n7. Decking shall progress in the planned direction so the crew is always working from a known surface toward the active edge. The crew shall not outrun the opening controls, the drop zone below, or the communication plan with the hoisting crew.\n\n8. At each break in the operation, the foreman shall decide whether the edge remains active or whether the zone is to be closed, barricaded, or otherwise secured for the next crew.\n\n4. Stop-Work and Escalation Criteria\n\n1. Work shall stop if the receiving steel is not stable, if the tie-off method cannot be maintained as planned, if the access route changes unexpectedly, or if wind or visibility prevents controlled movement at the edge.\n\n2. Work shall stop if an unauthorized employee enters the restricted leading edge zone, if deck spread outruns securement and opening control, or if the crane route begins exposing workers below or beside the edge.\n\n3. Work shall stop if the crew cannot clearly identify whether the area is still an active steel-erection leading edge or has become an uncontrolled opening or incomplete deck condition.\n\n5. Documentation and Records\n\n1. Daily pre-task plan identifying the leading edge location and sequence.\n\n2. Inspection record or foreman verification that the area, anchor method, and access route were checked.\n\n3. Training record for employees assigned as connectors or deck-leading-edge workers.\n\n4. Site sketch or release note when a controlled area is opened or closed.\n\n6. Emergency and Response Requirement\n\nIf a fall or near-fall occurs, all movement at the edge shall stop. The fall rescue plan shall be activated immediately, the area below shall remain controlled, and the foreman shall preserve the scene well enough to identify what condition changed before the event.\n\n7. Review, Retraining, and Program Updates\n\nThis program shall be reviewed with the crew before the start of each leading edge phase, whenever the decking direction or fall protection method changes, and whenever the project introduces a new access method or new trade interface.",
