    "moduleKey": "steel_fall_rescue_and_suspension_trauma_program",
    "title": "Fall Rescue and Suspension Trauma Program",
    "plainText": "FALL RESCUE AND SUSPENSION TRAUMA PROGRAM\n\nStep-by-step emergency program for worker recovery after a fall during steel erection or decking operations\n\nPrimary basis: employer duty to provide hazard training, fall protection procedures, emergency action readiness, and competent response planning under 29 CFR 1926.20, 1926.21, 1926.35, 1926.760, and fall system criteria used with steel erection.\n\n1. Program Purpose and Applicability\n\nThis program applies whenever personal fall arrest or fall restraint equipment is used, whenever a worker may be left suspended after a fall, and whenever steel erection methods create a rescue need that cannot be solved by ordinary site first aid alone.\n\nThis program is triggered before any shift where workers may be exposed to a fall requiring active retrieval, assisted self-rescue, aerial lift recovery, ladder-assisted recovery, rope rescue, or fire department support.\n\n2. Roles and Responsibilities\n\n1. The steel erection foreman shall make sure the rescue method matches the work height, access path, anchor method, and equipment in use before employees leave the ground or a protected surface.\n\n2. The competent person shall verify that the rescue path is realistic for the exact work phase and that the site has not relied on outside emergency services as the only immediate rescue method unless that arrangement has been specifically confirmed and timed.\n\n3. Designated rescue-capable personnel shall know their role, the equipment staging point, the communication method, and the worker lowering or retrieval sequence to be used for the day.\n\n4. All exposed employees shall know how to report a fall immediately, how to keep the area clear for rescue, and how to avoid creating a second fall or struck-by event during the response.\n\n3. Required Pre-Task Steps and Field Procedure\n\n1. Before work starts, identify the expected rescue method for the task. The method may involve self-rescue, assisted rescue from an adjacent protected surface, recovery by aerial lift, or other preplanned retrieval method, but the method shall match the exact work location and not a generic site assumption.\n\n2. Stage the rescue equipment where it can be reached quickly without crossing the same unprotected hazard that caused the original fall exposure. Equipment shall be inspected before the shift and kept separate from damaged or out-of-service gear.\n\n3. Confirm emergency communication. The crew shall know who calls 911, who directs site responders to the exact location, who controls the area below, and who begins immediate retrieval actions if the preplanned method allows it.\n\n4. If a worker falls and remains suspended, the nearest worker shall report the event immediately and shall not disconnect or alter the system unless directed by the rescue lead or unless doing so is part of the preplanned assisted rescue method.\n\n5. The rescue lead shall assess whether the worker is conscious, injured, in contact with steel or equipment, or in a position that requires a lift, ladder, or mechanical retrieval rather than simple assisted self-rescue.\n\n6. The area below and around the suspended worker shall be controlled to prevent secondary struck-by and dropped-object exposure. Hoisting in the area shall stop unless the hoisting equipment is part of the approved rescue method.\n\n7. Retrieve the worker using the preplanned method. The goal is prompt recovery to a safe surface while avoiding sudden release, pendulum movement, or an unprotected transfer that creates a second fall.\n\n8. Once the worker is on a safe surface, first aid, EMS coordination, and transport decisions shall follow the site medical response procedure. Any fall arrest equipment involved shall be removed from service until a competent person determines its status.\n\n4. Stop-Work and Escalation Criteria\n\n1. Suspend all nearby steel erection activity during the rescue unless a specific piece of equipment is needed to execute the retrieval.\n\n2. Stop any attempted rescue method that requires improvisation beyond the training and equipment available; switch immediately to the next approved method and call outside responders if required.\n\n3. Stop work for the remainder of the affected phase until the crew understands why the event occurred and the foreman confirms the area is safe to re-enter.\n\n5. Documentation and Records\n\n1. Rescue contact sheet with emergency numbers and access directions.\n\n2. Shift-specific rescue method or notation tied to the pre-task plan.\n\n3. Inspection record for rescue equipment and fall protection equipment in use that shift.\n\n4. Post-incident report documenting response time, retrieval method, equipment used, and required corrective action.\n\n6. Emergency and Response Requirement\n\nSuspension trauma risk increases with time. The employer shall treat a suspended worker as an urgent medical and rescue event, not merely a reporting event. Rescue planning shall therefore focus on immediate retrieval capability at the work face instead of assuming delayed outside response will be enough.\n\n7. Review, Retraining, and Program Updates\n\nThis program shall be reviewed before each phase using fall arrest systems, whenever the access method changes, whenever an employee changes work elevation or anchor method, and after every fall, near miss, or rescue drill.",
