    "moduleKey": "steel_multiple_lift_rigging_program",
    "title": "Multiple Lift Rigging Program",
    "plainText": "MULTIPLE LIFT RIGGING PROGRAM\n\nStep-by-step field program for multiple-member picks, separation control, connector coordination, and release discipline\n\nPrimary basis: 29 CFR 1926.753(e), including multiple lift rigging procedure requirements and qualified-rigger duties.\n\n1. Program Purpose and Applicability\n\nThis program applies when the erection crew uses multiple lift rigging to hoist more than one similar member on a single assembly during steel erection.\n\nThis program is triggered before the first multiple lift of the shift and remains active until the final multiple-member pick is complete.\n\n2. Roles and Responsibilities\n\n1. The foreman shall verify that the members selected for multiple lift rigging match the permitted method, are staged in the right order, and are going to receiving locations ready for the sequence.\n\n2. The qualified rigger shall confirm that the multiple lift rigging assembly and its components are properly rated, inspected, and assembled for the exact pick configuration.\n\n3. Connectors receiving the lift shall know which member comes off first, where the hook will remain during slackening, and how the line of fire is controlled while individual members are released.\n\n4. The operator shall keep the lift controlled and shall refuse the pick whenever spacing, swing, wind, or receiving conditions create doubt.\n\n3. Required Pre-Task Steps and Field Procedure\n\n1. Before the pick, confirm that the selected members are suitable for multiple lift rigging and that the receiving crew is ready for the exact release order.\n\n2. Inspect the multiple lift rigging assembly and all components before the shift and before use after any change or impact. The qualified rigger shall remove questionable components from service.\n\n3. Assemble the load with the required spacing and hardware. The crew shall avoid improvised arrangements that change how the lower member behaves when the line is slackened for release.\n\n4. Review the release sequence with the receiving crew before the lift leaves the ground. The crew shall know which member will be connected first and where each worker will stand while the assembly is tensioned and relaxed.\n\n5. Move the load along the planned route and keep non-essential workers out of the path. Because several members are moving at once, the drop zone and swing envelope shall be treated as larger than a normal single-member pick.\n\n6. Land the lift at the receiving line and connect members in the approved order. The hook shall not be released until the member being disconnected has reached the required stable connection condition for that phase.\n\n7. After each multiple lift, review whether the method remained controlled. Any unusual member movement, rigging shift, or release problem shall be corrected before the next multiple lift.\n\n4. Stop-Work and Escalation Criteria\n\n1. Stop the multiple lift if the assembly spacing, hardware, or inspection status cannot be verified.\n\n2. Stop the lift if the receiving condition is not ready, if the crew cannot maintain the approved release order, or if the lower member behaves unpredictably when the line is slackened.\n\n3. Stop work if wind or congestion makes it impossible to keep the larger suspended assembly under control.\n\n5. Documentation and Records\n\n1. Qualified-rigger verification or certification documents maintained by the employer for the assembly in use.\n\n2. Shift-specific lift notation identifying that multiple lift rigging will be used.\n\n3. Inspection record or daily confirmation for the assembly and its components.\n\n4. Corrective action note for any uncontrolled movement or sequence problem.\n\n6. Emergency and Response Requirement\n\nIf the assembly shifts unexpectedly or a member cannot be safely released, the operator shall regain tension and stabilize the lift while the foreman clears the area and re-evaluates the method.\n\n7. Review, Retraining, and Program Updates\n\nThis program shall be reviewed before every shift using multiple lift rigging and whenever the assembly, member type, receiving crew, or release order changes.",
