    "moduleKey": "steel_open_web_joist_and_bridging_program",
    "title": "Open Web Joist and Bridging Program",
    "plainText": "OPEN WEB JOIST AND BRIDGING PROGRAM\n\nStep-by-step field program for joist placement, release control, bridging sequence, and early-load prevention\n\nPrimary basis: 29 CFR 1926.757 and related stability and fall protection provisions in Subpart R.\n\n1. Program Purpose and Applicability\n\nThis program applies to open web steel joists and joist girders, including landing, seat connection, required field bolting, bridging installation, and the point at which the line may receive deck or other loads.\n\nThis program is triggered before the first joist of the phase is hoisted and remains active until the joist line has reached the required stabilized condition for decking or later loading.\n\n2. Roles and Responsibilities\n\n1. The foreman shall verify span, seat condition, release sequence, and required bridging steps before the first joist is lifted.\n\n2. The competent person shall confirm the supporting structure is ready and shall inspect any joist line left incomplete at shutdown or after weather changes.\n\n3. The rigging and receiving crew shall not release the hoisting line until the joist has reached the connection condition required by the standard and the project sequence.\n\n4. Deck crews and material handlers shall not assume a joist line is ready for bundles or spread loads until the foreman releases it for that purpose.\n\n3. Required Pre-Task Steps and Field Procedure\n\n1. Review the joist details, span, and release rule for the exact line being erected. The crew shall know whether the line depends on stabilizer details, bridging, or both before the hook can be released and before later loads can be added.\n\n2. Inspect the support seats and the receiving line before the pick. The crew shall not start with uncorrected support problems.\n\n3. Hoist the joist in a controlled manner and land it onto the prepared support points. Maintain body position that avoids pinch and fall exposure during seat engagement.\n\n4. Install the required field connection condition before hook release. The crew shall not rely on the appearance of the seat alone to decide the joist is stable.\n\n5. Install bridging and stabilizing elements in the required sequence. The line shall not be treated as ready for deck bundles, deck spread, or other material loading until the required stabilization has occurred.\n\n6. At shutdown, inspect every incomplete joist line and leave it in a safe condition that matches expected overnight wind and site exposure.\n\n4. Stop-Work and Escalation Criteria\n\n1. Stop work if the joist cannot be seated cleanly, if the release rule for that line is unclear, or if the required stabilizing step is not available when needed.\n\n2. Stop work if anyone attempts to land deck bundles or other concentrated loads onto a line that has not been released for that purpose.\n\n3. Stop work if weather, support movement, or material misfit changes how the joist behaves during landing or release.\n\n5. Documentation and Records\n\n1. Joist erection sequence or joist placement notes.\n\n2. Foreman verification of stabilization status before decking or bundle loading.\n\n3. Inspection notes for incomplete joist lines left overnight or after wind events.\n\n4. Corrective action report for any joist roll, release problem, or early-load violation.\n\n6. Emergency and Response Requirement\n\nIf a joist rolls, shifts, or cannot be safely stabilized, all employees shall clear the line, the hoisting crew shall maintain or regain control if possible, and the foreman shall reset the method before additional joists are handled.\n\n7. Review, Retraining, and Program Updates\n\nThis program shall be reviewed before every joist phase, whenever the span or support condition changes, and before any deck or material load is introduced onto the line.",
